---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import PageHero from '../components/PageHero.astro';
import { site } from '../data/site';

// Table of contents — the 13 articles. Anchors match each <section id> below.
const toc = [
  { id: 'name', label: 'I. Name' },
  { id: 'constitution', label: 'II. Constitution & Bylaws' },
  { id: 'organization', label: 'III. Organization & Offices' },
  { id: 'authority', label: 'IV. Congregational Authority' },
  { id: 'membership', label: 'V. Church Membership' },
  { id: 'officers', label: 'VI. Officers' },
  { id: 'meetings', label: 'VII. Church Meetings' },
  { id: 'ordinances', label: 'VIII. Ordinances' },
  { id: 'resource-teams', label: 'IX. Standing Resource Teams' },
  { id: 'other-teams', label: 'X. Other Church-Life Teams' },
  { id: 'budget-funds', label: 'XI. The Budget & Funds' },
  { id: 'indemnification', label: 'XII. Indemnification' },
  { id: 'amendments', label: 'XIII. Amendments' },
];
---
<Base
  title="Church Bylaws"
  description="The Bylaws of Chelsea Community Church — how we are organized, led, and held accountable: Christ ruled, elder led, and congregationally accountable."
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="About"
    title="Church Bylaws"
    lead="How Chelsea Community Church is organized, led, and held accountable — Christ ruled, elder led, and congregationally accountable."
  >
    <a class="btn btn--outline" href={site.bylaws} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Official document ↗</a>
  </PageHero>

  <div class="wrap bylaws-wrap">
    <aside class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
      <p class="toc-title">Contents</p>
      <ol class="toc-list">
        {toc.map((t) => (
          <li><a href={`#${t.id}`}>{t.label}</a></li>
        ))}
      </ol>
    </aside>

    <div class="bylaws-body">
      <section class="article" id="name" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article I</p>
        <h2>Name</h2>
        <p>This organization shall be known as "Chelsea Community Church."</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="constitution" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article II</p>
        <h2>Constitution and Bylaws</h2>
        <p>The Constitution of Chelsea Community Church (hereinafter referred to as the "Church") declares who we are and consists of our purpose, our statement of faith, our covenant of fellowship, and our core values. These Bylaws prescribe the governance of the Church, under the leadership of the Holy Spirit, as vested in its members and administered by the Board of Elders and our pastoral staff. Wherever possible, these Bylaws shall be interpreted so as to be consistent with the Constitution. Should any bylaw be found to contradict a provision of the Constitution, the Constitution shall control.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="organization" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article III</p>
        <h2>Organization, Incorporation and Offices</h2>
        <h3>A. Organization</h3>
        <p>Chelsea Community Church is organized and incorporated under the laws of the state of Alabama.</p>
        <h3>B. Offices</h3>
        <p>Although Chelsea Community Church meets regularly for worship services and community groups on multiple campuses, its legal and official address is: 101 Chelsea Park Drive, Chelsea, Alabama 35043.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="authority" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article IV</p>
        <h2>Congregational Authority</h2>
        <p>Chelsea Community Church shall be Christ ruled, elder led, and congregationally accountable, with its governance vested in its members and administered by the Board of Elders and the pastoral staff. To that end, the members shall have the sole authority to perform the following actions:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Calling of the Senior Pastor and members of the pastoral staff</li>
          <li>Electing members of the Board of Elders</li>
          <li>Electing members of the Board of Trustees and Church Clerk</li>
          <li>Adopting an annual budget</li>
          <li>Buying or selling property</li>
          <li>Borrowing money in excess of 5% of the annual church budget</li>
          <li>Amending the Constitution</li>
          <li>Amending these Bylaws</li>
          <li>Addressing any other matter that, in the opinion of the Board of Elders, should come before the congregation for approval.</li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="membership" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article V</p>
        <h2>Church Membership</h2>

        <h3>A. How Members Are Received</h3>
        <p>Chelsea Community Church strives to be a body of believers comprised of persons who profess a personal faith in the Lord Jesus Christ, having received baptism in a church as defined in the New Testament, and who actively follow Him in discipleship. The Church receives into membership those who come as a result of the Lord's leadership and are willing to meet the following requirements:</p>
        <ol type="a">
          <li>Express a personal faith in Jesus Christ as Lord and Savior, evidenced by a changed life and a growing desire for intimacy and holiness before God.</li>
          <li>Participate in the church's new member orientation program, becoming acquainted with the history, doctrine, and governance of the Church and its opportunities for service.</li>
          <li>Meet with the Senior Pastor or his designee to discuss the above and any other concerns.</li>
          <li>Present themselves before the congregation for membership on the recommendation of the Senior Pastor or his designee, to be formally accepted and confirmed by the church body.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Individuals may be received into membership by baptism following a public profession of faith, by statement of faith, or by restoration following an action of church discipline.</p>

        <h3>B. Rights of Members</h3>
        <p>Every member is entitled to vote at all elections and on all questions submitted to the Church in conference, provided the member is present. Proxy voting is prohibited. Every member is eligible for consideration by the membership as a candidate for the elective offices of the Church, in accordance with Scripture.</p>

        <h3>C. Responsibilities of Members</h3>
        <p>Members are generally expected to joyfully participate in the following:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Be present during worship and prayer services.</li>
          <li>Be in prayer for the leadership of the church, one another, and brothers and sisters in Christ around the world.</li>
          <li>Exhibit love for all the body.</li>
          <li>Be involved in true Christian community through our community groups and/or other means.</li>
          <li>Serve the congregation as individually gifted and impassioned.</li>
          <li>Provide financially for the ministries of the church through tithes and offerings.</li>
          <li>Be watchful over and encourage one another toward holiness.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>D. How Members May Be Dismissed</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Membership may be terminated through death, transfer of membership to another church, or voluntary resignation.</li>
          <li>If a member does not attend any service of worship, Bible study, or prayer meeting for an extended period and, after being contacted about the non-attendance, continues to be absent for an additional three (3) months, membership may be reluctantly terminated. Exceptions are made for the aged, homebound, those serving in the military, or those away at college.</li>
          <li>Any member found guilty and unrepentant after church discipline (Section E) may be dismissed by vote of the Church.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>E. Church Discipline and the Restoration Process</h3>
        <p>Recognizing that the Bride of Christ is called to be pure and holy, the Church administers, when necessary, church discipline as outlined in Scripture. Disciplinary action is directed toward any member known to be committing acts not characteristic of Christian conduct, or who consistently upsets the unity of the church. Discipline is pursued in the hope that an erring brother or sister will repent and be restored. Administering discipline is the responsibility of the Board of Elders, which brings any necessary recommendation before the Church. The process includes:</p>
        <ol type="a">
          <li>An initial, private, one-on-one admonition by a member with personal knowledge of ongoing improper conduct.</li>
          <li>If unresolved, a second admonition in the presence of one or two Elders.</li>
          <li>A reasonable effort to secure a private resolution so that public censure is not required.</li>
          <li>If steps a–c do not result in repentance and restoration, and if the Board of Elders so recommends, a call for public correction before the gathered church at a special called meeting. If this also fails, the member may be (1) publicly admonished, (2) removed from leadership positions, (3) expelled from fellowship, (4) restricted from Communion, and (5) have membership terminated by a two-thirds (2/3) majority of the voting members present.</li>
          <li>If at any point the accused repents and makes appropriate restitution, restoration is considered accomplished.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>If, after dismissal through discipline, an individual becomes repentant, publicly confesses their previous wrongdoing, and makes any appropriate restitution, the Church will consider the offense removed; the disciplinary process is ended, and the individual may again request membership per Section A.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="officers" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article VI</p>
        <h2>Officers</h2>
        <p>According to Scripture, the biblical officers of the Church are the pastoral staff, Elders, and Deacons. In addition, these Bylaws recognize the administrative positions of Trustee, Clerk, and Treasurer as officers. All officers must be members of the Church in good and regular standing prior to their nomination.</p>

        <h3>A. Pastoral Staff</h3>
        <h4>1. Senior Pastor</h4>
        <p>The Senior Pastor is a permanent voting Elder and performs the duties of an Elder. He is recognized as one who, in response to God's call, has devoted his vocational life full-time to the ministry of the Word and prayer. He is qualified as an elder — of satisfactory biblical training, high moral reputation, and evident spiritual discernment and gifts — and subscribes without mental reservation to the Statement of Faith, the Constitution, and these Bylaws.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><b>Selection.</b> Upon a vacancy, the Board of Elders constitutes an Advisory Senior Pastor Search Committee of three to five members in good standing (spouses of active elders and anyone in the regular pay of the church may not serve). The committee recommends a candidate to the Board of Elders, which chooses a candidate to recommend to the congregation; the candidate is elected by a majority of votes cast at a congregational meeting called for that purpose. Compensation is set by the Board of Elders in consultation with the Personnel Team, within the adopted budget.</li>
          <li><b>Role.</b> The counsel of the Senior Pastor is sought by the officers and ministries of the Church, and the office is held in honor and respect. With the Board of Elders and other pastoral staff, he oversees the spiritual welfare of the congregation.</li>
          <li><b>Duties.</b> He has responsibility for the teaching ministry in Sunday morning worship; may recommend to the Board the creation, termination, or change of pastoral and ministerial positions; may appoint other staff within the adopted budget; and may delegate duties while retaining oversight. The Board of Elders retains oversight of the Senior Pastor.</li>
          <li><b>Termination.</b> The Senior Pastor may dissolve the pastoral relationship at any time, giving one month's notice in good faith unless a shorter period is agreed upon.</li>
          <li><b>Grievance.</b> Any member may bring a grievance against the Senior Pastor to the Board of Elders. If, after thorough investigation, the Board believes the grievance true and substantial, it calls a special congregational meeting. His call may be terminated given all of: (1) a Board recommendation for removal; (2) attendance of at least thirty percent (30%) of the voting membership; and (3) a two-thirds (2/3) majority vote by ballot. Unless otherwise recommended, compensation of not less than one-twelfth of his annual compensation is provided.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>2. Other Pastoral Staff</h4>
        <p>Upon recommendation of the Board of Elders, the congregation may call other pastoral staff to direct and oversee particular ministries. Candidates meet the same qualifications as an elder and are elected by a majority of votes cast at a congregational meeting. Duties are stipulated in writing by the Board and reviewed at least annually. Any pastoral staff member may dissolve the relationship with one month's notice; except for the Senior Pastor, the Board of Elders may terminate a pastoral relationship by an eighty percent (80%) majority vote of all its voting members.</p>

        <h3>B. Board of Elders</h3>
        <p>The Board of Elders consists of lay elders from the congregation and staff elders from the paid pastoral staff, with primary responsibility for the spiritual oversight of the body. It comprises no fewer than five (5) and no more than nine (9) members in good standing who meet the qualifications of I Timothy 3:1-7 and Titus 1:5-9. The majority of the Board shall be lay elders who are not paid staff. All decisions are reached after prayerful consideration, in a spirit of humility, moving toward the goal of unity (Philippians 2:3-4).</p>
        <h4>1. Lay Elders</h4>
        <p>Lay elders are men who are members of the Church, twenty-five (25) years of age or older, who have been members for at least three (3) years. They are nominated by the Senior Pastor, examined by the full Elder Board, and referred to the congregation for confirmation by majority vote. Lay elders are voting elders and in all cases constitute a majority of the Board. Terms are three years and may be renewed.</p>
        <h4>2. Staff Elders</h4>
        <p>The Senior Pastor is a permanent voting member of the Board. Other pastoral staff may serve as elders from time to time, subject to the same scriptural qualifications; except for the Senior Pastor, staff elders serve in a non-voting status. They are nominated by the Senior Pastor and confirmed by the congregation; terms are three years and may be renewed.</p>
        <h4>3. Organization, Meetings, and Quorum</h4>
        <p>Annually the Board elects a chair, a vice-chair, and such other officers as needed. Regular meetings are held monthly. Special meetings may be called by the chair, vice-chair, or a majority of elders, with at least one day's notice (waivable in writing by all members). A quorum is a majority of all members, provided at least three voting members are present; the acts of the majority of voting elders present are the acts of the Board. The Board keeps records of its meetings and decisions and informs the congregation of all major decisions.</p>
        <h4>4. Duties</h4>
        <p>The Board of Elders has power and authority to act for the Church, except as limited by these Bylaws, directly or by delegation. In providing spiritual oversight it shall:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Care for the Church's spiritual condition, guard the purity of its doctrine and life, and, when necessary, discipline in accordance with the Word of God.</li>
          <li>Ensure that all who seek membership are properly examined per Article V.</li>
          <li>Act on behalf of the Church in the acceptance and dismissal of members, maintaining the membership roll with the Church Clerk.</li>
          <li>Counsel the erring and needy, comfort the sick and afflicted, and share in the responsibility of supplying the pulpit.</li>
          <li>Be responsible for the regular services of the Church and the observance of Baptism and the Lord's Supper.</li>
          <li>Ordain, commission, and/or license a minister according to the needs of the Church and the requirements of law.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The Board also provides guidance to the pastoral staff in developing the Church budget presented to the members, establishes priorities for the use of resources, has direct oversight of the benevolence and missions funds (Article XI), and may delegate authority to committees or teams under a written policy describing their makeup, responsibilities, authority, and duration.</p>
        <h4>5. Limitations</h4>
        <p>The Board shall not assume any of the prerogatives reserved to the members (Article IV) unless provided by the Constitution or these Bylaws, or unless given express congregational consent.</p>
        <h4>6. Termination</h4>
        <p>An elder's office is vacated upon death, resignation, or removal by the Board. The Board may remove an elder by an eighty percent (80%) majority vote of all other voting members. Grounds include: failure to fulfill designated responsibilities (including excessive absences from meetings); disturbing the purity, peace, or unity of the Church; a change in views regarding the Statement of Faith; or failure to live in harmony with the standards of the Constitution and these Bylaws.</p>

        <h3>C. Deacons</h3>
        <p>Deacons are members of the Church, twenty-one (21) years of age or older, recommended by the congregation, examined by the Board of Elders for suitability per I Timothy 3:8-13 and Acts 6:1-7, and appointed according to their giftings by the Board of Elders. Any member may recommend a member for consideration as a Deacon; the Board selects nominees who possess the qualifications and will serve willingly if elected. Deacons are appointed for one-year terms unless otherwise specified.</p>
        <p>The principal duty of Deacons is to form and lead the various Deacon Teams established by the Board of Elders for the care of the congregation — for example, teams for Shut-Ins, Outreach, Hospital Visitation, Widows and Widowers, Member Care, and Benevolence. Deacons shall not assume prerogatives reserved to the congregation unless authorized. A Deacon's office is vacated upon death, resignation, or removal by an eighty percent (80%) majority vote of all voting members of the Board of Elders, on grounds parallel to those for elders.</p>

        <h3>D. Other Officers and Leadership Positions</h3>
        <h4>1. Church Clerk</h4>
        <p>The Church Clerk is elected by the congregation upon recommendation of the Board of Elders for a three-year term and may serve successive terms. The Clerk must be a member (and may be a member of the staff) and is responsible for keeping and publishing Church records, maintaining the current membership list as determined by the Board, recording the minutes of all congregational meetings, and keeping official correspondence. The Clerk provides for the safekeeping of all papers and documents of the Church and ensures that members have access to all Church governing documents — including the Constitution, these Bylaws, and all policies, resolutions, and other governing documents. Removal follows the same process as for a Deacon.</p>
        <h4>2. Church Treasurer</h4>
        <p>The Church Treasurer is the Lay Elder designated to serve as Chairman of the Finance Team. The Treasurer ensures that all authorized bills are paid and that a full account is kept of all monies received and paid out, submits regular reports to the Board of Elders on the financial condition of the Church, and prepares a written annual report at the close of each fiscal year. The Treasurer ensures that the financial records of the Church are reconciled annually — whether by audit or other satisfactory means — and makes the financial records available for examination at any time upon request by the Board of Elders.</p>
        <h4>3. Board of Trustees</h4>
        <p>The Board of Trustees comprises those Elders currently in service who are not in the regular pay of the church, together with no more than three (3) church members in good standing elected at-large by the congregation for three-year terms. Trustees are bonded for the protection of the Church's interests. They are legally responsible for the legal and financial interests and all real property of the Church, and hold in trust the titles and legal papers to all Church property (originals kept in a bank safe deposit box, copies in the Church office). Trustees serve as signatories in legal and financial matters; the signatures of at least two Trustees, one of whom must be a member-at-large, are required to enter into any legal contract on behalf of the Church.</p>

        <h3>E. Ministers</h3>
        <p>Ministers are ministry leaders who are not considered officers of the Church. Upon recommendation of the Board of Elders, the congregation may call individuals as ministers in response to specific needs and in recognition of their spiritual gifts; a minister is called by a majority of votes cast at a congregational meeting. Responsibilities are stipulated in writing and reviewed at least annually. A minister may dissolve the relationship with one month's notice; the Board of Elders may terminate a ministerial relationship by an eighty percent (80%) majority vote of its voting members.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="meetings" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article VII</p>
        <h2>Church Meetings</h2>
        <h3>A. Worship Services</h3>
        <p>The Church meets regularly each Sunday morning at all campus locations, and on specifically scheduled Wednesday evening services, for the purposes of preaching, teaching, evangelism, and the worship of Almighty God. These meetings are open to everyone and conducted under the direction of the Senior Pastor.</p>
        <h3>B. Special Services</h3>
        <p>All Church meetings essential to the objectives and core values of the Church are placed on the Church calendar, published in the bulletin and website at least once prior, and announced at all services on the Sunday prior.</p>
        <h3>C. Regular Business Meetings</h3>
        <p>A business meeting is held at least annually to consider such matters as the adoption of the annual budget and the election of Elders. Notice is published in the bulletin and on the website at least one week before the meeting and announced at all services on the Sunday prior.</p>
        <h3>D. Special Business Meetings</h3>
        <p>A specially called business meeting may be held to consider matters of a significant nature, with notice of the subject, date, time, and location published at least one week before and announced on the Sunday prior.</p>
        <h3>E. Quorum</h3>
        <p>A quorum consists of the Church members who attend the business meeting, provided it is a regular meeting or one that has been properly called.</p>
        <h3>F. How Meetings Are to Be Conducted</h3>
        <p>Business meetings are conducted with a sense of decency, civility, and order (1 Corinthians 14:40) and with an attitude of love and selflessness. If a meeting begins to become disorderly, the Moderator calls for a time of prayer. At the Moderator's discretion, Robert's Rules of Order may be used to promote orderliness in areas not addressed by the Constitution and these Bylaws.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="ordinances" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article VIII</p>
        <h2>Ordinances</h2>
        <p>The Church observes two ordinances — Baptism and the Lord's Supper.</p>
        <h3>A. Baptism</h3>
        <p>Believer's Baptism is a symbolic act of obedience that identifies the believer with the death, burial, and resurrection of Jesus. A person who receives Jesus Christ as Savior by personal faith, professes Him publicly at a worship service, and commits to follow Him as Lord may be received for baptism upon consultation with the Senior Pastor or designated pastoral staff. Baptism is by immersion in water, administered by the Senior Pastor or whomever he designates, as an act of worship during any worship service, and scheduled as soon as reasonably possible after the candidate's public confession of faith.</p>
        <h3>B. The Lord's Supper</h3>
        <p>The Lord's Supper is a symbolic act of obedience whereby members, through partaking of the bread and fruit of the vine, commemorate the death of Jesus Christ and anticipate His Second Coming. It is observed at the discretion of the Senior Pastor, but no less than once per calendar quarter, with the Senior Pastor, pastoral staff, church staff, and Elders primarily responsible for its administration.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="resource-teams" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article IX</p>
        <h2>Standing Church Resource Teams</h2>
        <h3>A. Finance Team</h3>
        <p>The Finance Team provides oversight and accountability in the administration and stewardship of church finances. Its responsibilities are to assist staff in developing the Annual Church Budget, provide oversight of church finances, help develop and implement sound management procedures, ensure appropriate accounting procedures are in place and followed, and ensure that an audit of church finances is conducted on an annual basis. It is appointed by the Board of Elders (three to five members in good standing, three-year terms). At least one member is an active Elder serving as Chairman (the Treasurer), and at least one lay member of the Board of Trustees serves on it. The Senior Pastor and Executive Pastor are ex-officio advisors.</p>
        <h3>B. Personnel Team</h3>
        <p>The Personnel Team provides accountability and oversight of church personnel matters: assisting in developing and updating a church-wide personnel policy, recommending salaries and benefits to the Board of Elders and Finance Team, assisting with job descriptions, and, where appropriate, helping the Board resolve personnel disputes per approved policies. Composition mirrors the Finance Team (three to five members, three-year terms, chaired by an active Elder; Senior Pastor and Executive Pastor ex-officio).</p>
        <h3>C. Missions Team</h3>
        <p>The Missions Team assists the Board of Elders in disbursing funds allocated to the Missions Fund. It consists of five (5) members — at least one active Elder as Chairman and at least two representatives at large — all appointed by the Board of Elders. Its duties are to promote knowledge of and interest in missions, review supported missionaries and ministries at least once every three years, recommend the adoption of and support levels for missionaries and ministries, submit a proposed missionary budget for the coming fiscal year, and perform other duties as delegated. The Senior Pastor, Executive Pastor, and any pastoral staff with missions oversight are ex-officio members.</p>
        <h3>D. Campus Leadership Teams</h3>
        <p>Because Chelsea Community Church functions as one unified congregation operating in multiple campus locations, Campus Leadership Teams may be appointed at each campus at the discretion of the Board of Elders (not required at every campus). Their purpose is to give the Board insight and counsel on the specific and unique needs of a campus. Teams are appointed on the recommendation of the Senior Pastor (three to five members who regularly attend that campus, three-year terms), with at least one active Elder as Chairman; the Senior Pastor and the campus's Teaching Pastor serve ex-officio.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="other-teams" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article X</p>
        <h2>Other Church-Life Teams</h2>
        <p>Other non-standing teams may be needed from time to time to support the health of the Church in areas such as Discipleship, Campus Facilities, Outreach/Missions, and Special Events. Based on the recommendation of the Senior Pastor, the Board of Elders examines the need for the creation and dissolution of such teams; any team formed under this Article is created and appointed by the Board, which sets the terms of office at the time of commissioning. All church members in good standing are eligible to serve on such committees.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="budget-funds" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article XI</p>
        <h2>The Budget and Funds</h2>
        <h3>A. The Budget</h3>
        <p><b>Adoption.</b> Within two months prior to the beginning of the next calendar year, the Church adopts an annual budget of expenditures for that year.</p>
        <p><b>Expenditure Limitations.</b> The Board of Elders may make expenditures not previously approved in the annual budget, up to ten (10) percent of the current approved budget, provided funds are readily available and upon a two-thirds (2/3) affirmative vote of its voting members. Unbudgeted expenditures in excess of these amounts are referred to the Church for final action.</p>
        <h3>B. Funds</h3>
        <p><b>Missions Fund.</b> It is the policy of the Church that ten (10) percent of the Church budget be designated for missions, with disbursements overseen directly by the Board of Elders with the assistance of the Missions Committee.</p>
        <p><b>Benevolence Fund.</b> The Church maintains a Benevolence Fund overseen directly by the Board of Elders, which may delegate authority for it to the Senior Pastor or his designee.</p>
        <p><b>Other Funds.</b> The Board of Elders may create such other funds as are appropriate for the physical care of the members and for the mission of the Church.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="indemnification" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article XII</p>
        <h2>Indemnification</h2>
        <p>The Board of Elders may, at its discretion, indemnify and advance all or part of the Church-related expenses of an employee, Elder, officer, or agent of the Church.</p>
        <p>Subject to this Article, the Board may indemnify any member who serves or has served as an officer against claims, liabilities, expenses, and costs necessarily incurred in the defense, compromise, or settlement of an action or proceeding — civil or criminal — in which the person is made a party by reason of being or having been an officer, to the extent not otherwise compensated or reimbursed by insurance, if: (1) the person's conduct was in good faith; (2) the person reasonably believed the conduct was in the best interests of the Church, or at least not opposed to them; and (3) in any criminal proceeding, the person had no reasonable cause to believe the conduct was unlawful.</p>
        <p>The Church may not indemnify an officer, former or current, in a proceeding brought by or in the right of the Church in which the officer was adjudged liable to the Church, or was adjudged liable on the basis of having received an improper personal benefit.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="article" id="amendments" data-reveal>
        <p class="art-kicker">Article XIII</p>
        <h2>Amendments</h2>
        <p><b>Adoption.</b> The Constitution and these Bylaws, when adopted, supersede all previous Constitutions and Bylaws of the Church. They may be amended or changed if two-thirds (2/3) of the members present and voting at the Church Conference vote in favor, provided the proposed amendments were presented in writing at a previous Church Conference at least fourteen (14) days prior to the vote.</p>
        <p><b>Amendments and Record Retention.</b> A copy of the Constitution and these Bylaws is kept at all times with the records of the Church Clerk and in the Church office; any amendment or revision is prepared in writing by the Clerk, showing the date of adoption, and attached to the copies so kept. This also applies to any resolution passed for the permanent or temporary government of the Church.</p>
        <p><b>Distribution of Copies.</b> Upon request, the members of the Church shall be furnished copies of this Constitution and these Bylaws.</p>
      </section>

      <p class="bylaws-note">
        This page reproduces the Bylaws of Chelsea Community Church, Chelsea, Alabama, as a readable reference for our members and friends. The official copy is maintained by the Church Clerk, and — upon request — members are furnished copies of the Constitution and these Bylaws (Article&nbsp;XIII).
        {' '}<a href={site.bylaws} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View the official document ↗</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .bylaws-wrap {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr;
